Vladimir Putin and the Risk of a Third World War
San Francisco – On February 24, Russia’s invasion of Ukraine marked the beginning of what could destroy our civilization’s third world war.
Before the invasion, Russian President Vladimir Putin and Chinese President Xi Jinping held a lengthy meeting on February 4 – the day marking the start of China’s Lunar New Year celebrations and the Beijing Winter Olympic Games.
After the meeting, the two issued a carefully crafted 5,000-word document declaring a close partnership between their two countries.
This document is more powerful than any treaty and certainly required meticulous negotiations beforehand.
I am shocked that Xi seems to have fully authorized Putin to invade and launch the war in Ukraine.
He believes that his confirmation as China's lifelong ruler later this year will be merely a formality, and he is confident about it.
After consolidating all power in his hands, Xi meticulously planned a scheme to elevate himself to the level of Mao Zedong and Deng Xiaoping.
With Xi's support, Putin set out to achieve his lifelong dream in an incredibly brutal manner.
At nearly 70 years old, Putin feels that if he wants to leave a significant mark in Russian history, it must be now or never.
But his view of Russia's role in the world is distorted.
It seems he believes that Russian people need a tsar to blindly follow.
This system is the opposite of democratic societies, and this vision distorts the emotional and sentimental state of the Russian people's "soul."
In my childhood, I had many interactions with Russian soldiers who occupied Hungary in 1945.
I know that if you ask them for something, they would share their last piece of bread with you.
Later, in the early 1980s, I embarked on what I called my political philanthropy.
Initially, I established a foundation in my homeland Hungary, and then became actively involved in promoting the dissolution of the Soviet Empire.
By the time Mikhail Gorbachev took office in 1985, this dissolution had already begun.
I set up foundations in Russia as well, and subsequently in each of the newly independent republics.
In Ukraine, even before it became an independent country, I established a foundation.
I also visited China in 1984 and became the first foreigner allowed to establish a foundation there (I closed the foundation in 1989, shortly after the Tiananmen Square massacre occurred).
I do not personally know Putin, but I have closely followed his rise to power and am well aware of his cold and ruthless nature.
He reduced Grozny, the capital of Chechnya, to rubble, and now he threatens to do the same to Kyiv, the capital of Ukraine.
Putin was once a shrewd KGB agent, but recently it seems he has changed.
It appears he has lost touch with reality because he has formed a fixed mindset.
There can be no doubt that he misjudged the situation in Ukraine.
He thought that Ukrainian speakers would open their arms to welcome Russian soldiers, but it turned out they were no different from the Ukrainian-speaking populace.
In the face of what seemed like an overwhelming likelihood, Ukrainians still showed incredible resistance.
In July 2021, Putin published a long article claiming that Russians and Ukrainians were actually one people, and that Ukrainians had been misled by neo-Nazis.
Since Kyiv was the original site of the Russian Orthodox Church, the first part of his argument was not historically unfounded.
But in Part 2, it is Putin who is misled.
He should have known the facts better.
Many Ukrainians fought bravely during the Euromaidan protests that erupted in 2014.
The events of 2014 enraged him.
But when ordered to attack their Ukrainian brothers, the Russian army performed poorly.
The Defense Ministry's corruption, deep-rooted as it is, also played a significant role in this poor performance.
But instead of blaming himself, Putin seemed to have lost his mind.
He was determined to punish Ukraine in retaliation, and his actions appeared to be bound by no constraints.
He threw the entire Russian army into battle, disregarding all rules of engagement, especially bombing civilian populations indiscriminately.
Many hospitals were attacked, and the power grid supplying electricity to the Chernobyl nuclear plant (which is currently occupied by Russian forces) was also destroyed.
In besieged Mariupol, up to 4 million people have gone without water and food for nearly a week.
Russia is likely to lose this war.
The US and EU are sending defensive weapons to Ukraine while trying to purchase MiG fighters that Ukrainian pilots know how to operate.
This could change the entire situation.
No matter the outcome, Putin has already achieved a miracle in strengthening Europe's resolve and unity.
At the same time, it seems that Xi has realized that Putin has strayed.
On March 8, after Chinese Foreign Minister Wang Yi insisted that Sino-Russian friendship remained "as solid as ever," Xi called French President Emmanuel Macron and German Chancellor Olaf Scholz to express his support for their peacekeeping efforts.
To avoid a humanitarian crisis, he hopes to exercise maximum restraint in the war.
It remains uncertain whether Putin will comply with Xi's wishes.
We can only hope that before Putin and Xi destroy our civilization, they will be removed from power.
